"Sun S., Bleck R.","Atlantic thermohaline circulation and its response to increasing CO2 in a coupled atmosphere-ocean model",2001,"Geophysical Research Letters","28","22",,"4223","4226",,,10.1029/2001GL013325,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0035891688&partnerID=40&md5=8463b6afbd169a3a2f5fd818236cfdf4","NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, NM, United States","Sun, S., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY, United States; Bleck, R., Los Alamos National Laboratory, Los Alamos, NM, United States","We discuss aspects of the Atlantic thermohaline circulation (THC) and its response to increased greenhouse gas concentration, using a coupled atmosphere-ocean general circulation model (AOGCM) whose oceanic component is a new hybrid-isopycnal model. Two 200-year model integrations are carried out - a control run assuming fixed atmospheric composition and a perturbation run assuming gradual doubling of CO2. We employ no flux corrections at the air-sea interface, nor do we spin up the ocean prior to coupling. The surface conditions in the control run stabilize after several decades. When doubling CO2 at the rate of 1% per year, the model responds with a 2°C increase in global mean surface air temperature (SAT) after 200 years and a virtually unchanged Atlantic meridional overturning circulation. The latter is maintained by a salinity increase that counteracts the effect of global warming on the surface buoyancy.",,"Atmospheric composition; Global warming; Greenhouse effect; Marine couplings; Salinity measurement; Surface buoyancy; Geophysics; carbon dioxide; air temperature; atmosphere-ocean coupling; carbon dioxide; salinity; thermohaline circulation; air temperature; Atlantic Ocean; circulation; greenhouse gas; model; ocean environment; thermohaline; Atlantic Ocean",,,,,,"Bleck, R., Boudra, D.B., Initial testing of a numerical ocean circulation model using a hybrid (quasi-isopycnic) vertical coordinate (1981) J. Phys. Oceanogr, 11, pp. 755-770; Bleck, R., Rooth, C., Hu, D., Smith, L., Salinity-driven thermocline transients in a wind- and thermohaline-forced isopycnic coordinate model of the North Atlantic (1992) J. Phys. Oceanogr, 22, pp. 1486-1505; Bleck, R., An oceanic general circulation model framed in hybrid isopycnic-Cartesian Coordinates (2001) Ocean Modelling, , in press; Cheng, W., (2000) Climate Variability in the North Atlantic on Decadal and Multi-Decadal Time Scales: A Numerical Study, , Ph.D. Dissertation, University of Miami, 153pp; Dixon, K.W., Lanzante, J.R., Global mean surface air temperature and North Atlantic overturning in a suite of coupled GCM climate change experiments (1999) Geophys. Res. Lett, 26, pp. 1885-1888; Gent, P., Will the North Atlantic Ocean thermohaline circulation weaken during the 21st century? (2001) Geophys. Res. Lett, 28, pp. 1023-1026; Hansen, J., Forcings and chaos in interannual to decadal climate change (1997) J. Geophys. Res, 102, pp. 25679-25720. , and 42 co-authors; Hansen, J., Climate forcings in GISS SI2000 simulations (2001) J. Geophys. Res, , submitted; (1996) Climate Change 1995, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), Houghton, J. T., L. G. Meira, B. A. Callander, N. Harris, A. Kattenberg, and K. Maskell (eds), Cambridge Univ. Press; Knutti, R., Stocker, T.F., Influence of the thermohaline circulation on projected sea level rise (2000) J. Climate, 13, pp. 1997-2001; Latif, M., Roeckner, E., Mikolajewicz, U., Voss, R., Tropical stabilization of the thermohaline circulation in a greenhouse warming simulation (2000) J. Climate, 13, pp. 1809-1813; Levitus, S., Burgett, R., Boyer, T.P., (1994) NOAA World Ocean Atlas 1994, 3-4. , 99 and 117 pp., Natl. Oceanogr. Data Cen., Washington DC; Manabe, S., Stouffer, R.J., Multiple-century response of a coupled ocean-atmosphere model to an increase of atmospheric carbon dioxide (1994) J. Climate, 7, pp. 5-23; Manabe, S., 